.SH "NAME"
die \- show message (success or error) with symbol (âœ“, x respectively) based on status code, unless QUIET is set and exit
.SH "SYNOPSIS"
.sp
.nf
\fBdie\fP [\fIOPTION\fP]... [\fIOPTION PROGRAM OUTPUT\fP]... [MESSAGE]...
\fBdie\fP \-\-desc|\-\-description|\-\-examples|\-\-help|\-\-manrepo|\-\-subsections|\-\-synopsis|\-\-version
.fi
.br
.SH "DESCRIPTION"
.sp
The \fBdie\fP command based on the previous exit code, will call \fBerror(1)\fP or \fBsuccess(1)\fP
to show arguments in \fIMESSAGE\fP and \fIexit\fP.
.br
.sp
Success and error messages are shown by default unless \fIQUIET=1\fP.
.br
.if n .sp
.RS 4
.it 1 an-trap
.nr an-no-space-flag 1
.nr an-break-flag 1
.br
.ps +1
.B Caution
.ps -1
.br
.sp
Use a variable and \fBdo not use command substitution in the message\fP when \fIfalse || die\fP,
since previous error code is overwritten by the command substitution return code.
.br
\fI$\fP cd "$(dirname "${input}")" 2>/dev/null || die Directory not Found: "$(dirname "${input}")"
.sp .5v
.RE
